Project Diary — Yamaha PSR-F51

Entry 01 — Initial Inspection

Date: 28/06/2026

I started documenting the internal structure of a Yamaha PSR-F51 keyboard with several failing keys.

The main goal was to investigate why many keys were not producing sound correctly. The issue appears to have developed gradually over several years, which suggests that the problem may be related to contact degradation, dirt, humidity, oxidation, or wear in the key contact system.

Observed Symptoms

- Several keys produce weak or no sound
- The failure affects a large part of the keyboard
- The problem appeared gradually over time
- Some keys still work, which suggests that the entire keyboard is not completely dead

Initial Hypotheses

Possible causes considered:

- Dirty contacts
- Rubber membrane degradation
- Fault in the key matrix
- Loose connector
- Oxidation
- Main board issue

At this stage, no final cause has been confirmed.

Initial Procedure

The keyboard was opened carefully for visual inspection.

I observed:

- The key assembly
- The internal board area
- The wiring
- The contact region
- The general internal structure

I also wrote handwritten notes to organize the diagnostic process before attempting any deeper repair.

Current Status

The project is currently paused.

The keyboard will be reassembled and stored safely. I plan to return to this project later after studying more electronics, multimeter usage, hardware diagnosis, and possibly robotics.

Future Work

Future steps may include:

- Numbering all keys from left to right
- Creating a table of working and failing keys
- Testing continuity with a multimeter
- Cleaning contact areas safely
- Studying keyboard matrix scanning
- Documenting the repair attempt
- Exploring future automation or robotics integration